---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base
  title="About — Cranes Consulting | Tyler Alexander, Tampa FL"
  description="Cranes Consulting is led by Tyler Alexander, a Lean Six Sigma Black Belt with 10+ years leading enterprise programs in federal healthcare and emergency response."
>
  <section class="border-b border-navy-100">
    <div class="container-x py-20 md:py-24 grid lg:grid-cols-12 gap-12 items-start">
      <div class="lg:col-span-7">
        <span class="eyebrow">About</span>
        <h1 class="mt-6 text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-[56px] font-extrabold tracking-tightest text-balance leading-[1.05] text-navy-900">
          Federal-grade program discipline, brought to Tampa's small businesses.
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg text-ink-soft leading-relaxed">
          Cranes Consulting was founded on a simple observation: the operating rigor that runs a $100M federal healthcare program doesn't need to cost $100M to implement. The frameworks are the same — risk registers, stage gates, KPI governance, standard work — the difference is how you scale them down without losing the discipline.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="lg:col-span-5">
        <div class="rounded-2xl bg-navy-900 text-white p-8 relative overflow-hidden">
          <div aria-hidden="true" class="absolute -right-16 -bottom-16 h-56 w-56 rounded-full bg-amber-400/10 blur-3xl"></div>
          <p class="relative text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-amber-300">Founder</p>
          <p class="relative mt-3 text-2xl font-bold">Tyler Alexander</p>
          <p class="relative mt-1 text-sm text-navy-100">Lean Six Sigma Black Belt</p>

          <div class="relative mt-8 grid grid-cols-2 gap-4 text-sm">
            <div>
              <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest text-navy-300">Based</p>
              <p class="mt-1 text-white">Tampa, FL</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest text-navy-300">Experience</p>
              <p class="mt-1 text-white">10+ years</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest text-navy-300">Sector depth</p>
              <p class="mt-1 text-white">Federal healthcare, IT modernization, emergency response</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest text-navy-300">Methodology</p>
              <p class="mt-1 text-white">DMAIC, Agile, Prosci ADKAR</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Bio -->
  <section class="container-x py-20 md:py-24 grid lg:grid-cols-12 gap-12">
    <div class="lg:col-span-4">
      <span class="eyebrow">Background</span>
      <h2 class="mt-5 text-3xl md:text-4xl font-extrabold leading-[1.1]">A decade running programs that can't fail.</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="lg:col-span-8 prose-custom">
      <p>
        Most of my career has been spent inside large federal healthcare organizations, leading enterprise-scale programs where the failure mode wasn't a missed quarter — it was a national headline. That environment forces a particular kind of rigor: every initiative has a risk register, every deliverable has an audit trail, every system integration has a compliance sign-off.
      </p>
      <p>
        On a federal Office of Emergency Management team, I led the design and implementation of an enterprise analytics program supporting nationwide emergency operations — the kind of program where governance, secure data infrastructure, and cross-functional alignment aren't "nice to have," they're the job. Earlier, on a national healthcare transformation team, I managed enterprise programs integrating multiple systems for 10+ national program offices, tracking 75+ KPIs across federal healthcare operations.
      </p>
      <p>
        What I kept noticing: small businesses have the exact same operational failure modes as federal programs — shelfware technology, missed handoffs, invisible margin leaks, runaway change orders, no single source of truth — but they rarely have access to the discipline that prevents them. <strong>That's the gap Cranes Consulting exists to close.</strong>
      </p>

      <h3>Methodology</h3>
      <p>
        The core toolkit is Lean Six Sigma — specifically, the DMAIC cycle for measurable improvement work, and Prosci's ADKAR framework for the change management side. Program governance uses standard PMP-aligned practices: risk registers, stage-gate reviews, stakeholder mapping, and clearly-defined RACIs. Data and reporting are built in Power BI, SQL, or whatever stack the client already runs.
      </p>
      <p>
        None of this is proprietary. The frameworks are public; the value is in the judgement about which lever to pull, when, and how to scale it to a small-business context without creating the bureaucracy of the frameworks' original settings.
      </p>

      <h3>Why "Cranes"</h3>
      <p>
        Cranes are known for precision, patience, and unusual lift capacity — traits that describe both the work and the outcome we want for our clients. The logo is a flying crane, neck extended forward, because the best operating improvements come from looking ahead, not behind.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Certifications -->
  <section class="bg-bone-200/60 border-y border-navy-100">
    <div class="container-x py-20 md:py-24">
      <span class="eyebrow">Credentials</span>
      <h2 class="mt-5 text-3xl md:text-4xl font-extrabold leading-[1.1]">Certifications &amp; training.</h2>

      <div class="mt-12 grid md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
        {[
          { name: 'Lean Six Sigma Black Belt', issuer: 'Certified' },
          { name: 'Prosci Change Management', issuer: 'Certified Practitioner' },
          { name: 'Project Management Professional (PMP)', issuer: 'In progress' },
          { name: 'HL7 FHIR Fundamentals', issuer: 'Health Level 7 International' },
          { name: 'Healthcare Analytics Certificate', issuer: 'Nebraska Methodist College' },
          { name: 'B.S. Kinesiology', issuer: 'Southeastern Louisiana University' },
        ].map((c) => (
          <div class="card p-5">
            <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-navy-800">{c.name}</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-ink-mute">{c.issuer}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Principles -->
  <section class="container-x py-20 md:py-24">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <span class="eyebrow">How I work</span>
      <h2 class="mt-5 text-3xl md:text-4xl font-extrabold leading-[1.1]">Principles that show up in every engagement.</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
      {[
        { t: 'Evidence, not opinions', d: 'Every recommendation is grounded in a measured baseline. If a claim can\'t be supported by data, it gets flagged as a hypothesis, not a finding.' },
        { t: 'Scope discipline', d: 'I only build what\'s asked. MVP first, iterate based on signal. No enterprise bloat. No speculative features. You aren\'t going to need it.' },
        { t: 'Respect the team', d: "The people running your operation daily know things I don't. The first week of any engagement is mostly listening." },
        { t: 'Clean exits', d: 'Every engagement ends with a team that can run the new operating rhythm without me. That\'s the measure of success.' },
      ].map((p) => (
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-navy-800">{p.t}</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-ink-soft leading-relaxed">{p.d}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container-x pb-24">
    <div class="rounded-2xl bg-navy-900 text-white px-8 py-14 md:px-14 md:py-20 flex flex-col md:flex-row md:items-center gap-6 justify-between">
      <div class="max-w-xl">
        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-extrabold">Let's see if we're a fit.</h2>
        <p class="mt-2 text-navy-100">30 minutes. No deck. Bring a real problem.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/contact" class="btn-accent shrink-0">Book a fit call</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
